        <div xml:id="AN24-kilavi"></div>
        <div xml:id="AN24">
            <lg type="edition"><l><choice><seg>vēḷāp</seg><seg>vēḷārp</seg></choice> pārppāṉ vāḷaran tumitta</l>
<l><choice><seg>vaḷaikaḷain</seg><seg>vaḷaikaḻin</seg></choice> toḻinta koḻunti ṉaṉṉa</l>
<l>taḷaipiṇi yaviḻāc curimukiḻp pakaṉṟai</l>
<l>citaralan tuvalai tūvaliṉ malarun</l>
<l>taii niṉṟa taṇpeyaṟ kaṭainā<supplied>ḷ</supplied></l>
<l>vayaṅkukatir karanta vāṭai vaikaṟai</l>
<l>vicumpuri vatupōl viyaliṭat toḻuki</l>
<l>maṅkuṉ māmaḻai teṉpulam paṭarum</l>
<l>paṉiyiruṅ kaṅkulun tamiya <choice><seg>ṇīnti</seg><seg>ṇīntit</seg></choice></l>
<l><choice><seg><supplied>ta</supplied>ṉṉū</seg><seg>tammū</seg></choice> rōḷē <choice><seg>naṉṉuta</seg><seg>naṉṉutal</seg></choice> <choice><seg>liyāmē</seg><seg>yāmē</seg></choice></l>
<l>kaṭimatiṟ katavam pāytaliṟ ṟoṭipiḷantu</l>
<l><supplied>nu</supplied>timuka <choice><seg>maḻuṅkiya</seg><seg>maḻukiya</seg></choice> maṇṇai veṇkōṭṭuc</l>
<l>ciṟukaṇ yāṉai neṭunā voṇmaṇi</l>
<l>kaḻipiṇik kaṟaittōṟ poḻikaṇai <choice><seg>yutaippuḻit</seg><seg>yutaipput</seg></choice></l>
<l>taḻaṅkukuraṉ muracamoṭu <choice><seg>mayaṅkum</seg><seg>muḻaṅkum</seg></choice> yāmattuk</l>
<l>kaḻittuṟaic ceṟiyā vāḷuṭai <choice><seg>yeṟuḻttō</seg><seg>yēṟuttō</seg></choice></l>
<l>ḷiravuttuyiṉ maṭinta tāṉai</l>
<l>yuravucciṉa vēntaṉ pācaṟai <choice><seg>yēmē.</seg><seg>yōmē.</seg></choice></l></lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>On the last day of permanent cool raining, in the month of Tai,</l>
<l>when the jalap with curly buds that had not [yet] opened [their] tight fetters</l>
<l>blooms because of the diffuse miserable spattering spray,</l>
<l rend="indent">	like splinters(?)<note place="foot">koḻuntu is a word only attested two times in the corpus, and the NA passage (224.3) does not help here. According to the dictionaries, it refers to something young, tender and growing, like a sprout, but context seems to demand a different meaning here: the old commentary simply glosses with caṅkiṉ talai, “the tip of a conch”. Incidentally the whole image is an early testimony for the traditional explanation of the brahmin as bangle-maker, who cuts bangles from conches (such as they are available in India up to this day) – an occupation permissible to him when he cannot live as a priest.</note> left behind, removed from the conch bangles</l>
<l rend="indent">	that are cut by the saw of a non-sacrificing brahmin,</l>
<l>swimming alone all the chilly dark night,</l>
<l rend="indent">	when the great rain with the clouds sets out for the southern fields,</l>
<l rend="indent">	having flown over the vast area as if the sky was stripped</l>
<l rend="indent">	by dawn<note place="foot">The idea conveyed implicitly by these two lines seems to be that lightning, the usual accompaniment of rain, illuminates the sky as bright as in daytime.  The north wind, vāṭai, could be the agent of urivatu and thus integrated into the image, but since it at the same time is said to hide the sun, it is more likely a concomittant to the movement of the clouds.</note>, with the north wind that hides the glowing [sun] rays,</l>
<l>[she with a] good forehead [is] in her village.</l>
<l rend="indent">	We,</l>
<l>passing midnight disturbed by drums with resounding voices,</l>
<l rend="indent">	during an alarm [due to] arrows showering the stained hides fixed with handles,</l>
<l rend="indent">	with long-tongued bright bells [sounding] on small-eyed elephants</l>
<l rend="indent">	with white tusks, dull since the points<note place="foot">nutimukam: this is one more example of mukam (literally “face”) used to denote the sharp edge of a weapon as in the striking passage in KT 227 where the chariot wheels cutting down the flowers on their route are described as vāḷ mukam.</note> of [their] tips became blunted,</l>
<l rend="indent">	tusk-rings bursting open when parting the doors of protected fortresses,</l>
<l>[are] in the encampment of the strong angry king</l>
<l rend="indent">	with an army that drooped off into sleep at night,</l>
<l rend="indent">	with mighty arms holding a sword not kept in the sheath.</l>
<l rend="indent"></l></lg>
        </div>
